         <abstract>
            <p>The so-called "Ḫāylu Compilation" is a compilation of chronicles and other historiographic works begun by <persName ref="PRS5222haylaMi"/> by collecting manuscripts and commissioning copies after
               a fire at the Royal Palace in <placeName ref="LOC3577Gondar"/> destroyed many manuscripts. 
               The actual "Ḫāylu Compilation" was produced during a later exile in <placeName ref="LOC4432Mahdar"/> by
               <persName ref="PRS5222haylaMi"/>'s friend and secretary <persName ref="PRS1007Abagaz"/>. After ending his compilatory work with the time of the exile in
               <placeName ref="LOC4432Mahdar"/>, <persName ref="PRS1007Abagaz"/> continued by writing himself the history of <persName ref="PRS5222haylaMi"/> and of Ethiopia,
               stopping after the death of <persName ref="PRS5222haylaMi"/> in <date>1809</date>, which is not included in the Compilation.
            Some manuscripts contain brief accounts of events taking place after <date>1809</date>, but these do not form part of the original Compilation.
               Most of the works included in the Ḫāylu Compilation also circulate independently.</p>
         </abstract>
